This is a rifled barrel extension for the Nerf Strongarm. I had two hopes when I started this design.

  1. Modifiable for future add-ons/customization.
  2. Range extension of the darts being fired.

Of those the modifiability of the design I believe works but could also still be improved to incorporate the standard Nerf adapter rather that the simple four guides I designed in to this. My ultimate goal in this is to add-on/alter the appearance of the gun to be something different, too which I'm leaning scifi-ish. In that - this I believe is a good start.

As to the range extension - well that I really haven't seen. Maybe a little in the standard Nerf darts, but the accustrikes already go pretty far and as it is the Strongarm fires a decent distance without the barrel. At the very least I can say it doesn't diminish distance - except on occasion when the cylinder doesn't quite line up right. That being said I've only experienced this with the accustrike darts and might be due as much to the cylinder as the head design of the dart.

Anyways I hope to continue to improve this and have included a short and long variation. Please note the barrel is fairly long and has very little surface contact with the bed. To this end I designed a support system for the printing. They barely touch the barrel and break away even as you remove the barrel from the bed, but it's enough. If you don't want to waste the material though and try without, I've included both versions with support and without.

Light sanding & Tape

I recommend lightly sanding the interior of the barrel with some sandpaper wrapped around a pencil or dowel.

In addition - while the barrel fits nicely in the strong arm - I designed it with a little wiggle room. I recommend wrapping some masking tape around the barrel below the ring, two to three wraps should be all that is needed. The ring is the point that shouldn't go past the insertion into the Strongarm. The tape I recommend is masking or other compressible tape. Because of the Nerf design that includes a lightly ridged interior barrel, the tape fills in those gaps and gives a tight fit.

title: Dremel Router with adjustable height + straight edge

description.text:
Saw a number of such routers but with all of them I had problems with routing a straight edge. So I designed one from scratch with a straight edge. Also made mine height adjustable using an insert (inner).

To use simply insert the inner into the outer and line up the groove in the inner with the screw hole. Insert a 4mm nut into the slot provided and use a 4mm screw. Screw the inner onto the Dremel head as shown and you can now adjust the height to your depth of cut by tightening the screw.

If you really need to see the markings, print in Black and paint the provided markings with white paint or print in any light colour and paint the markings in black.

To cut straight, simply fix a ruler or any straight edge and then run the flat surface along it as shown.

The venetian blinds in our house (we have 15 or so of them) are quite nice, being thick wooden blinds.
However, they all have a common flaw: part of the mechanism that enables them to rotate is a small plastic cam that holds the strings that has failed on every one of the blinds.
There are up to four of these small cams in each blind unit: we discovered to our dismay after moving in that nearly all of them had failed, and had been duct taped back together to make them look like they worked.
This works as a short-term fix, but the duct tape peels off and fails after a month or so, so we were constantly fixing these things.
Makerbot Replicator 2 to the rescue! I was able to extract the part from the blind assembly, and using my CAD software, designed a replacement.
I made the part thicker in the area that was failing, and also thickened the walls of the part to ensure its durability. It took a few iterations to get the size of the hexagonal hole correct (photo 2 - the cam needs to be a tight fit so that it doesn't slip), I had successfully created a viable replacement.
The money I saved by being able to fix these blinds with this simple part has more than paid for the Replicator 2!

Additional hardware required:

  1. M4 screw X 5-10mm long
  2. Tension coil spring (mine comes from a used laser printer cartridge)
  3. Double-sided tape (3M VHB tape recommended)

How it works:

When the power on the Cetus 3D printer is turned off, the horizontal arm will drop. When it reaches the arm of the shock absorber, the spring will extend to reduce the shock and bring the arm to a stop before it touches the print bed. During actual printing, the stepper motor is able to overcome the spring tension and reach the print bed so no user action is required whatsoever to operate the shock absorber.

It is recommended to place the arm of the shock absorber at a point below the stepper motor (move along the X-direction) such that the nozzle touches the print bed just before the arm reaches the bottom (adjust along the Y-direction).

The base of the shock absorber is stuck to the metal casing of the printer with strong double-sided tape.

P.S. A double spring version is included if the spring you can find do not have enough tension. For a video showing the shock absorber in action, goto https://youtu.be/I4b1CjHHJ4g

Printing recommendation:

As the hooks on the base and arms are going to take a lot of shock from the springs, it is recommended to print with as high an infill as you have time for. A 0.2mm layer height is good enough and both the base and the arm should be printed lying on its flat side.

CAUTION:

Remove the print nozzle when testing to find the right spring with enough tension. No part of the print head should touch the print bed when the horizontal arm is dropped and stopped by the shock absorber. For the extended Z-axis machines, the double spring version is recommended.

title: WordClock 12h (desk clock edition)
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
WordClock 12h (desk clock edition)

This provides a 3D printable desk frame for the awesome WordClock project maintained by users of the german µC.net forum. The WordClock will tell you the time in words in 5 minute increments and will light up the 4 dots in the corners for the minutes inbetween. You may have seen projects like this before or may have encountered the original "QLOCKTWO" by Biegert & Funk (see http://qlocktwo.com) somewhere. I built my first WordClock many years ago and thanks to users like Frank (ukw), Torsten (wawibu) and the others involved who put time, work and heart into this project it is still alive and evolving. They manage hardware bulk orders, help users and generally are a friendly bunch, so fire up Google translate in case you don´t speak german and visit us there for general project information or a friendly chat:

Help thread: https://www.mikrocontroller.net/topic/385955
Wiki project description: https://www.mikrocontroller.net/articles/WordClock_mit_WS2812

These Models are based on RomanBuchert´s awesome OpenSCAD Model. Thanks for sharing your awesome customizable Design! Without his script I would not have been able to release this. Get his original Design here: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1330897

To build a 3D printed WordClock 12h you need to have the following prerequisites:

The Hardware described on the project page (at least a STM32F103C8T6 and probably a Shield, a DS3231 RTC, an ESP8266 module - ESP-12F if you want the ability to update the Software OTA or an ESP-01 if you want to do this manually - and a 5V 3A Power supply) minus the wooden frame and plexiglass front obviously. Its all described in the Wiki and as long as you have a bit of soldering experience you should be fine. The models are designed to fit any printer with at least a 200x200mm printbed, which should fit almost any model out there.

The WordClock 12h (desk clock edition) comes in different flavours, so you can freely choose if you want to print a diffuser or have the front detachable. It consists of a front part with the printed letter matrix, a back part where you can fit in the electronics and a backplate to close the case and hide all the electronics. All supported language layouts are available, which means there is a german, a swiss german and two different englisch layouts available for download here. All of these are currently supported by the WordClock software.
The 3 Part version has cutouts in the back part for 12mm wide/1mm high neodymium magnets and the front part has a cutout to glue in a small steel washer or another small magnet. This is completely optional, you can use the combined parts or glue the front and back together if you dont want to switch out the front plate later, I just added them to give you more options. ;-) You could even use stuff like Tesa PowerStrips to mount the front and back part together or you could put your own custom diffuser between the front and back part (for example you could use a very thin paper - like greaseproof/sandwich paper? - if you can not print the diffuser with your printer or want the unlit characters to be more visible when printing in dark colors)... just be creative! :-)

PS: I have achieved the best results with a printed diffuser (less scattered light on the unlit neighbors and better readability from bigger viewing angles)

You will either need a front part in your desired language, the back part and a backplate or a combined front/back part and a backplate to build a complete desk clock.

WC12h_Desk_Clock_front_and_back_combined_with_diffuser_ENG2_layout.stl will print a whole case with a printed 0.2mm diffuser and the layout ENGLISH2 you can later choose in the software. Then print a backplate of your choice (Ambilight with 30 or 60 LEDs or a regular one) and youre done!

You will get the same thing - with a detachable front - if you print WC12h_Desk_Clock_front_part_with_diffuser_ENG2_layout.stl, WC12h_Desk_Clock_back_part_compatible_with_all_language_front_parts.stl and a backplate.

You will need to have your printer well calibrated (see http://reprap.org/wiki/Triffid_Hunter's_Calibration_Guide) and if you intend to print the diffuser version your printbed needs to be flat and perfectly leveled to get the best results. Apart from that a common 0.4mm nozzle, 3 perimeters, 15-20% infill and 0.2mm layer height is all you need, no special requirements here. When printing the front part in a light/bright color you might want to consider printing this part solid or adding a few extra top/bottom layers to better block light from shining through the material where it should not...

The filament I used was my default PETG material (I can recommend http://www.dasfilament.de for well pigmented PETG and http://www.3dpsp.de for a little more translucent PETG filament) and prefer light/bright or white colors, but other Filaments and dark colors should work too. You can print a 0.2mm layer and try if a LED behind that will shine through. I even have used black color 3DPSP PETG successfully for this.

When printing a Diffuser your first layer should look similar to this to get a good result (white PETG from dasfilament.de)

UPDATE: Added STLs compatible with 96 LED/m stripes. Filenames start with "96_" and the back covers should still be compatible.

You need at least 114 WS2812, SK6812 or APA102 LEDs for the display matrix. This model will match the spacing of a 90 LEDs/m (!) Stripe you can buy from eBay, Aliexpress (https://www.aliexpress.com/item/1m-2M-4M-5M-74-90-96-leds-m-5V-WS2812b-Pixels-Led-strip-Addressable-individual/32742526184.html) and other sources. That means the spacing between the LEDs is 11.11mm. You could also use those little LED Dots (I´ve used them for the 4 minute LEDs before, but 4 single LEDs of a stripe will work just fine) you can find on Aliexpress (https://www.aliexpress.com/item/colorful-led-Free-shipping-WS2812B-LED-With-Heatsink-10mm-3mm-DC5V-5050-SMD-RGB-WS2812-IC/32463398304.html) on the whole display matrix, but mounting and wiring will be quite a hassle. I´d recommend to use the 90LED/m stripe for the display and 4 single LEDs cut from the stripe for the minute dots. Everything else will probably work too, but means more work and will be way more difficult to solder/mount inside the back part. Just mount the Stripes on a small 135x135x1mm Aluminum or Steel plate (but make sure you don´t create any electrical shorts!), glue the plate in the back part model and mount the STM32 board and the other stuff on the other side of the plate. I hope you get the Idea... ;-)

Here are a few pics that show the process:

Preparing the stripes and Aluminum plate (1) Preparing the stripes and Aluminum plate (2) Rear view of the installed display matrix Display matrix ready to go :-)

I created Backplates that can make use of the Softwares second hand feature. There is a ring that will fit either 30 LEDs of a 60 LED/m stripe or 60 LEDs of a 144 LED/m stripe. With any of those two methods you can not only use the Ambilight feature to illuminate the case if you want (see pictures for examples), but also use the softwares feature of a "running dot" as second hand or get the ambilight filled/cleared within a minute. That means 60 LEDs will display accurate to the second while with 30 LEDs the second hand will jump every two seconds. This again is completely optional, but having a glowing case looks really awesome. Give it a try if you got the LEDs or money to buy them, you will not be disappointed! Go for the 60 LED version if youre not sure which one to use or what to buy.

Use 30 LEDs of a 60 LED/m stripe or 60 LEDs of a 144LED/m stripe to get a really nice Ambilight / Case illumination Ambilight in action! Another one, this time in blue... ... pink ... ... and green! Oh, did I already mention you can use the Ambilight / Case illumination to indicate the seconds? ;-)

If you use a filament that is very bright colored or translucent there is a chance that the LED will shine through its own light channel and illuminate the neighbour(s). Of course you can always turn down brightness, but you might want to consider spray painting the back part of the model with a light blocking color. I successfully used RAL9006 spraypaint and a primer to make it stick to the plastic. This will only cost a few bucks, but you should consider doing this if you want the Desk Clock to be perfect in the end when using bright/translucent fliament! If you plan to do this you should go for the separated front and back parts of course.

Info on filament used here:
When you take a close look on the pictures you will notice the front part and a bit of the back part are both white, but still somehow different. The reason is I printed the parts I wanted to block more light with the more pigmented white PETG from http://www.dasfilament.de (which I use for the diffuser too!) and used http://www.3dpsp.de white PETG for the rest, because its way more translucent on thicker walls. In combination this worked really great for me. Other filaments will work too, but you might have to experiment a little which ones work better for different lighting situations.

When printing the Backplate I usually print the first two layers with a clear filament, then switch to the desired color. Thats exactly what I did in the pictures above and I just love the looks!

Instead of the Aluminum or Steel plate you could also just print a small 135x135x1mm square. Heat dissipation should not be an issue, but I never tried this before. Leave a comment if you dared to try and it worked. :-)

When printing the Front you might want to consider printing it solid (complere or a few more layers then usual) to block more light where it should not shine through.

Light channels spraypainted in RAL 9006 and 12x1mm Neodymium magnets glued in Backplate: First two layers are clear PETG, then I switched to 3DPSP white, which I use whenever I want to light up something I printed

description.text: I made them in the form of a chocolate bar because they are easier to print this way. 100 nuts per print. Use a cutter to separate the nuts. The M5 screw will drill its own path in the hole of the nut. I built a complete MendelMax with these nuts and I can say they hold very well.

At first, I couldn't find the necessary T-slot nuts. Then, I found them at a very high price which I didn't liked. So I decided to find a substitute for the nuts and I designed this substitute using AutoCAD 2000. The first nuts I made, were separate and ready to use but the process of printing them was not very reliable, since some of them were distorted. Then I decided to make them under the form of a chocolate bar and after printing, to separate them using a cutter.

comments.text: I made them specially for the 20mm Misumi bars so they will fit. If you intend to print them, please bear in mind that several kinds of plastics don't fit the purpose too well. I guess it's a matter of the plastic expansion after cooling and it has something to do with the color pigments from within the plastic filament.

author: thx1138

description.text:
My girlfriend is a photographer and currently has an exhibition where she had to provide some flyers/directory of the pictures. Since we did not have anything to put the flyers in, I made her this :)

The flyer holder it self is cut from 10mm plywood, and the businesscard holder is 3d printed to hang from the lip of the holder.

I have designed the bottom part for a lock/cleat to fit in. However, the lock I had designed did not fit very well, and since everything holds perfectly together without a lock, I have not redesigned or uploaded it.

When not is use, the lip of the bottom part fits into the slot in the back part. I glued the lip onto the bottom part.

I designed it in freecad, and for some reason I can not export the cnc'ed part as dxf files. Instead I have uploaded them as step files.

For best surface finish make the slicer software perform retractions on the "inside" of the enclosure, where they are not visible. This can be done in Simplify3D by setting option "Choose start point closest to specific location" to a coordinate in the middle of the encoluse part.

Assembly

A lasercut, lightly tinted or transparent, 2 or 3 mm acrylic front glas is recommended. It should have the same outer dimensions as the "Front spacer" with the corner 3.5 mm holes (acrylic_front.svg).

Requires four M3x25mm screws for assembly. (M3x20mm if not using front acrylic)

Assembly instructions:

  1. Print the Enclosure, Board spacer and buttons in desired color.
  2. Print the Front spacer (black color recommended)
  3. Place the buttons in the buttons holes from the inside of the enclosure. Make sure they fit loosely, clear the holes with a 6mm drill if needed.
  4. Install the Run-DMD PICO pcb, make sure is seats firmly against the four corner bottom spacers of the enclosure. Verify that the buttons are "clickable".
  5. Place the "board spacer" so that is fits on the side over the SD card holder.
  6. Install the OLED display, make sure the connection pins are correctly inserted into the Run-DMD PICO pcb connector.
  7. Place the "front spacer" over the OLED display, verify that its corners are completely seated against the OLED displays pcb.
  8. Place the optional arcylic front glas on top over the OLED display and front spacer.
  9. Install the four M3 screws in the corner holes, do not over tighten!
  10. Verify that the four control buttons "feels correct", and all clicks when pressed.
  11. Install the micro SD-card. You may need to gently push it in with a small screwdriver to make it click in place.
  12. Install the CR2032 battery and then connect the USB power cable to a 5V source or computer.

description.text:
Updated 01/04/2018
There was a small glitch in both of ther top cover versions. It has now been corrected.

Updated 12/30/2017
So after a few test prints I've determeined that the V3 files were too tight of a fit and required too much filing to get a proper fit. I have adjusted for this and the new V4 files should not require any filling to fit.

Also I've added another version of the spine that has cutouts behind the dice locations for inserting N45 1/2" x 1/16" Neodymium magnets like the ones linked below.
https://www.ebay.com/itm/N45-1-2X1-16-w-3M-Adhesive-on-1-2-North-South-SAMPLER-20-PC-/322475681402?hash=item4b150c667a
The magnets will need to be dropped in at layer heights 35.8mm and 94.8mm. This will allow steel or Iron Fill printed dice to stick to that part of the spine. It makes for a cool illusion when the book is opened and the dice are already located.

Updated 12/23/2017 Merry Christmas!!!
I've posted a Version 3 of all the files (make sure you get the files dated 12/24/2017 I didn't realize I had a previous V3 version of the discard box). These are redesigned so that all three covers can be printed standing up (supports required). This will provide for a more uniform look to the outside of the box. The covers are then cut out so that the draw and discard boxes can be glued and inserted in place. The new version spine fixed a few printing errors and as before has the "Volume 1" removed so you can emboss as you desire. Supports will also be needed when printing the discard box but only touching the printbed (for the notch at one end to clear the hinge). Oh yea and I took "The Gathering" off the covers as none of my printers had much luck printing that with any legible quality(if anyone really wants it let me know and I'll add it back in).

Updated 4/10/17
By request I have created a spine without the Volume label. Unfortunately the spine I remixed had the Volume embedded in it and I could not just delete it so I had to slice, delete and copy it out. The new file is "Quick draw spine no volume" I have not had a chance to print it so please let me know if there are any problems.

Ok, So what started out as a friends request for a Magic card box turned into a massive remix. His final requirements were as follows.

  1. Must hold 100 Sleeved cards.. - Check
  2. Must have a Draw and Discard area. - Check
  3. Must Have storage for life counter dice. - Check
  4. Must look cool. - CHECK!!! CHECK!!! CHECK!!!

The book is printed in 5 pieces. I printed the Draw, discard, back and top covers flat on the print bead. This give you perfectly smooth and flat faces allowing the covers to easily be glued on with acetone. The hinges are still made to work with a standard piece of 1.75mm filament. I also created provisions in the top cover to allow for the mana of choice to be inserted. Mana Button files are provided as well.

I would imagine this could easily be adapted for any other card game (i.e. Uno, poker, blackjack, etc)

My thanks to Pteraghost for a great starting point to build from.

There are a few minor errors in the Discard side but it prints perfectly, I'm running a 6 year old computer with windows 10 and using Microsoft 3D builder and have reached my system limitations. I welcome anyone attempting to repair the file.

title: Dust collection for Taig CNC mill

description.text: Polycarbonate is great stuff to mill but the little gritty swarf gets everywhere. I also find that my 1/16" bits tend to wind up any strings of polycarbonate and eventually build up enough that they form a little puck of fused plastic around the tip that destroys the work surface. I built this attachment to take the tube from my shop vacuum and apply suction right next to the head on the mill. The photos and MP4 show it in action, it works pretty well (for those who are interested, it's cutting 3 mm polycarbonate with a 1/16" TiCN coated two-flute spiral at 10,500 rpm, feedrate 600 mm / minute). The polycarbonate sheet is being held in version 2 of my laser-cut fixture, previously posted as http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:20281

Print. Clean. Install. Use.
Should click into the T-slot on the right side of the Taig's milling head (slide it up from the bottom until the little lip clicks over the top). The hose from the shop vacuum (2" internal diameter) just slides in and friction-fits (the tube is slightly tapered).
There are some flaws in the mesh but nothing that interfered with the print. This one was done on an Objet 24 as we have one, but I'd be interested to see how it turns out on the DIY machines. It may need some solvent to fuse it together more strongly if printed by FDM. The worst stresses are around the T-slot mount.

title: P.I.N.D.A. PROTECTOR for 12mm Inductive proximity sensor LJ12A3-4-Z + VIDEO

description.text:
Read print notes please! Now with correct M12x1mm thread instead of M12x1.75mm.

I saw that Prusa has an additional thing on their website called a P.I.N.D.A. protector. A snag protector for an inductive proximity sensor for when a part of your print warps or peaks up and hits the probe.
Since the Prusa MK2 uses a smaller diameter probe, this does not fit on the widely used 12mm version LJ12A3-4-Z/BX or BY.
So I designed one using Autodesk's Fusion 360, as with many of my other things.
I hope you will enjoy it as well!

This sensor only detects metal print surfaces. When using a build mat like Buildtak or Lokbuild, you might want to upgrade to the LJ18A3-8-Z/BX dat detects up-to 8mm away (way less using alu beds). This way you 12mm version will not hit your prints and upset the positioning of the head/nozzle when a piece of the print sticks out a tiny bit. Because the bottom of the sensor will be basically at the same height at the tip of the nozzle.
You'll thank me later. :)

Subscribe to my channel: see this thing getting printed here, with some behind the scenes Fusion 360 footage. ;).

Hi this is a Head phone mount that can slip on to a shelf or on to a desk. These are design to just slip on to a shelf or desk with no effort and hold themselves in place using the materials properties to allow it to act as the spring locking mechanism.

I have two different designs for this one is smaller and does not require anything more than slipping on to the shelf but you may have trouble with different thicknesses of shelves as it was design for a particular size in mind. the second is the larger design is more adaptable as it a spring design in to the product with a hook which allows the user to pull the spring back and slide on to the shelf this allows for a tighter fit on to the shelf and stops it from being knocked off.

I hope you enjoy the design and if you have any feedback on this design it would be very helpful to hear it, this is my first design on thingiverses so any tips you have for me would be great.
